Date: 30/4/1918
Source: Wanganui Chronicle
Author:
Vol / Page: 4
Edition:
Quote: The common method of addressing a New Zealander is to call him "digger," which, from being an abusive term, has been readily and universally adopted and approved by the Pig Islanders themselves. We, the N.Z.R.B., prefer to be addressed as "diggers" rather than "dinks" which was the original mode of address.
Notes: From a letter by Rifleman C A Palmer of Wanganui (nb: date entered in NZDE database was 31/4/1918)

Date: 13/8/1917
Source: Wanganui Herald
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: "Digger" is now the common form of salutation between privates. It applied to the Maoris only at one time. They do a lot of pioneer work, such as digging trenches, but as we all do more or less navvy work, the term is universally used among the New Zealanders. Really the meaning is "Friend" now.
Notes: This is from a letter from an Auckland soldier;

